{"action": "edit", "code": "def find_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and returns the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of four integers (minx, miny, maxx, maxy) representing the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid == blue)\n    minx, miny = np.min(blue_points, axis=1)\n    maxx, maxy = np.max(blue_points, axis=1)\n    return (minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    minx, miny, maxx, maxy = find_blue_points(input_grid)\n    grid1 = color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    line_num = find_blue_points_within_area(grid1, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    output_grid = color_line_black_points_red(grid1, minx, miny, maxx, maxy, line_num)\n    return output_grid\ndef color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    for i in range(minx, maxx + 1):\n        if input_grid[i][miny] == black:\n            input_grid[i][miny] = red\n        if input_grid[i][maxy] == black:\n            input_grid[i][maxy] = red\n    for j in range(miny, maxy + 1):\n        if input_grid[minx][j] == black:\n            input_grid[minx][j] = red\n        if input_grid[maxx][j] == black:\n            input_grid[maxx][j] = red\n    return input_grid\ndef color_line_black_points_red(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int, line_num: List[int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid, the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid, and a list of integers representing the same column or row of all the blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge).\n    It tests if the row or column line_num has more than one blue points. All black points that are in the line and within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] are colored red.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    line_num: A list of integers representing the same column or row of all the blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge).\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors with all black points that are in the line and within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] colored red.\n    \"\"\"\n    if len(line_num) > 1:\n        if line_num[0] == line_num[-1]:\n            input_grid[line_num[0], miny + 1:maxy] = red\n        else:\n            input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, line_num[0]] = red\n    return input_grid\ndef find_blue_points_within_area(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> List[int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n    It finds all the blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge) and returns their same column or row.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A list of integers representing the same column or row of all the blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge).\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, miny + 1:maxy] == blue)\n    if len(blue_points[0]) == 0:\n        return []\n    if blue_points[0][0] == 0:\n        return blue_points[1].tolist()\n    if blue_points[1][0] == 0:\n        return blue_points[0].tolist()\n    return []", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray: \n    minx,miny,maxx,maxy = `find all blue points in the grid, return its min x,min y, max x, max y coordinate`(input_grid)\n    grid1 = `Color the black points in the edge of area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] red`(input_grid,minx,miny,maxx,maxy)\n    line_num = `find all blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge), return their same column or row`(grid1,minx,miny,maxx,maxy)\n    output_grid = `test if row line_numcolor or column line_num have more than one blue points.All black points that in the line and within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] red`(grid1,minx,miny,maxx,maxy,line_num)\n    return output_grid\n\ndef color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    for i in range(minx,maxx + 1):\n        if(input_grid[i][miny] == black):\n            input_grid[i][miny] = red \n        if(input_grid[i][maxy] == black):\n            input_grid[i][maxy] = red \n    \n    for j in range(miny,maxy + 1):\n        if(input_grid[minx][j] == black):\n            input_grid[minx][j] = red\n        if(input_grid[maxx][j] == black):\n            input_grid[maxx][j] = red\n    \n    return input_grid\n    ", "gpt_code": "def find_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and returns the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of four integers (minx, miny, maxx, maxy) representing the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid == blue)\n    minx, miny = np.min(blue_points, axis=1)\n    maxx, maxy = np.max(blue_points, axis=1)\n    return (minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\ndef color_line_black_points_red(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int, line_num: List[int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid, the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid, and a list of integers representing the same column or row of all the blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge).\n    It tests if the row or column line_num has more than one blue points. All black points that are in the line and within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] are colored red.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    line_num: A list of integers representing the same column or row of all the blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge).\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors with all black points that are in the line and within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] colored red.\n    \"\"\"\n    if len(line_num) > 1:\n        if line_num[0] == line_num[-1]:\n            input_grid[line_num[0], miny + 1:maxy] = red\n        else:\n            input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, line_num[0]] = red\n    return input_grid\ndef find_blue_points_within_area(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> List[int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n    It finds all the blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge) and returns their same column or row.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of all the blue points in the grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A list of integers representing the same column or row of all the blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge).\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, miny + 1:maxy] == blue)\n    if len(blue_points[0]) == 0:\n        return []\n    if blue_points[0][0] == 0:\n        return blue_points[1].tolist()\n    if blue_points[1][0] == 0:\n        return blue_points[0].tolist()\n    return []", "holes": {"find_blue_points": "find all blue points in the grid, return its min x,min y, max x, max y coordinate", "color_line_black_points_red": "test if row line_numcolor or column line_num have more than one blue points.All black points that in the line and within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] red", "find_blue_points_within_area": "find all blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge), return their same column or row"}}
{"action": "edit", "code": "def find_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and returns the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of four integers (minx, miny, maxx, maxy) representing the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid == blue)\n    minx, miny = np.min(blue_points, axis=1)\n    maxx, maxy = np.max(blue_points, axis=1)\n    return (minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    minx, miny, maxx, maxy = find_blue_points(input_grid)\n    grid1 = color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    x, y = find_blue_points_within_area(grid1, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    output_grid = color_black_points_red_in_row_or_column_with_more_than_two_blue_points(grid1, x, y, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    return output_grid\ndef color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    for i in range(minx, maxx + 1):\n        if input_grid[i][miny] == black:\n            input_grid[i][miny] = red\n        if input_grid[i][maxy] == black:\n            input_grid[i][maxy] = red\n    for j in range(miny, maxy + 1):\n        if input_grid[minx][j] == black:\n            input_grid[minx][j] = red\n        if input_grid[maxx][j] == black:\n            input_grid[maxx][j] = red\n    return input_grid\ndef color_black_points_red_in_row_or_column_with_more_than_two_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray, x: int, y: int, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Check whether the part row x or column y within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge) has more than two blue points, color all black points red in that row or column.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    x: An integer representing the x coordinate of the blue point within the area.\n    y: An integer representing the y coordinate of the blue point within the area.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of the area.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of the area.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of the area.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of the area.\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors with all black points in the row or column with more than two blue points colored red.\n    \"\"\"\n    row = input_grid[x + 1:maxx, y]\n    col = input_grid[x, y + 1:maxy]\n    if np.count_nonzero(row == blue) > 2:\n        input_grid[x + 1:maxx, y][input_grid[x + 1:maxx, y] == black] = red\n    elif np.count_nonzero(col == blue) > 2:\n        input_grid[x, y + 1:maxy][input_grid[x, y + 1:maxy] == black] = red\n    return input_grid\ndef find_blue_points_within_area(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of an area and returns the coordinates of the blue point within that area.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of the area.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of the area.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of the area.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of the area.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two integers (x, y) representing the coordinates of the blue point within the area.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, miny + 1:maxy] == blue)\n    if blue_points[0].size == 0:\n        return (-1, -1)\n    x, y = (blue_points[0][0] + minx + 1, blue_points[1][0] + miny + 1)\n    return (x, y)", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray: \n    (minx, miny, maxx, maxy) = find_blue_points(input_grid)\n    grid1 = color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    (x, y) = `find blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge), return its coordinate`(grid1,minx,miny,maxx,maxy)\n    output_grid = `Check whether the part row x or column y within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge) has more than two blue points, color all black points red in that row or column`(grid1,x,y,minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    return output_grid\ndef color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    for i in range(minx,maxx + 1):\n        if(input_grid[i][miny] == black):\n            input_grid[i][miny] = red \n        if(input_grid[i][maxy] == black):\n            input_grid[i][maxy] = red \n    \n    for j in range(miny,maxy + 1):\n        if(input_grid[minx][j] == black):\n            input_grid[minx][j] = red\n        if(input_grid[maxx][j] == black):\n            input_grid[maxx][j] = red\n    \n    return input_grid\n    ", "gpt_code": "def find_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and returns the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of four integers (minx, miny, maxx, maxy) representing the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid == blue)\n    minx, miny = np.min(blue_points, axis=1)\n    maxx, maxy = np.max(blue_points, axis=1)\n    return (minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\ndef color_black_points_red_in_row_or_column_with_more_than_two_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray, x: int, y: int, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Check whether the part row x or column y within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge) has more than two blue points, color all black points red in that row or column.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    x: An integer representing the x coordinate of the blue point within the area.\n    y: An integer representing the y coordinate of the blue point within the area.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of the area.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of the area.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of the area.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of the area.\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors with all black points in the row or column with more than two blue points colored red.\n    \"\"\"\n    row = input_grid[x + 1:maxx, y]\n    col = input_grid[x, y + 1:maxy]\n    if np.count_nonzero(row == blue) > 2:\n        input_grid[x + 1:maxx, y][input_grid[x + 1:maxx, y] == black] = red\n    elif np.count_nonzero(col == blue) > 2:\n        input_grid[x, y + 1:maxy][input_grid[x, y + 1:maxy] == black] = red\n    return input_grid\ndef find_blue_points_within_area(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of an area and returns the coordinates of the blue point within that area.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of the area.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of the area.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of the area.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of the area.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two integers (x, y) representing the coordinates of the blue point within the area.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, miny + 1:maxy] == blue)\n    if blue_points[0].size == 0:\n        return (-1, -1)\n    x, y = (blue_points[0][0] + minx + 1, blue_points[1][0] + miny + 1)\n    return (x, y)", "holes": {"find_blue_points": "find all blue points in the grid, return its min x,min y, max x, max y coordinate", "color_black_points_red_in_row_or_column_with_more_than_two_blue_points": "Check whether the part row x or column y within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge) has more than two blue points, color all black points red in that row or column", "find_blue_points_within_area": "find blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge), return its coordinate"}}
{"action": "edit", "code": "def find_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and returns the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of four integers (minx, miny, maxx, maxy) representing the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid == blue)\n    minx, miny = np.min(blue_points, axis=1)\n    maxx, maxy = np.max(blue_points, axis=1)\n    return (minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    minx, miny, maxx, maxy = find_blue_points(input_grid)\n    grid1 = color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    x, y = find_blue_points_within_area(grid1, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    output_grid = color_black_points_red_in_row_or_column_with_more_than_two_blue_points(grid1, x, y, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    return output_grid\ndef color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    for i in range(minx, maxx + 1):\n        if input_grid[i][miny] == black:\n            input_grid[i][miny] = red\n        if input_grid[i][maxy] == black:\n            input_grid[i][maxy] = red\n    for j in range(miny, maxy + 1):\n        if input_grid[minx][j] == black:\n            input_grid[minx][j] = red\n        if input_grid[maxx][j] == black:\n            input_grid[maxx][j] = red\n    return input_grid\ndef color_black_points_red_in_row_or_column_with_more_than_two_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray, x: int, y: int, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int):\n    row = input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, y]\n    col = input_grid[x, miny + 1:maxy]\n    if np.count_nonzero(row == blue) >= 2:\n        input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, y][input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, y] == black] = red\n    elif np.count_nonzero(col == blue) >= 2:\n        input_grid[x, miny + 1:maxy][input_grid[x, miny + 1:maxy] == black] = red\n    return input_grid\ndef find_blue_points_within_area(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of an area and returns the coordinates of the blue point within that area.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of the area.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of the area.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of the area.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of the area.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two integers (x, y) representing the coordinates of the blue point within the area.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, miny + 1:maxy] == blue)\n    if blue_points[0].size == 0:\n        return (-1, -1)\n    x, y = (blue_points[0][0] + minx + 1, blue_points[1][0] + miny + 1)\n    return (x, y)", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray: \n    (minx, miny, maxx, maxy) = find_blue_points(input_grid)\n    grid1 = color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid, minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    (x, y) = `find blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge), return its coordinate`(grid1,minx,miny,maxx,maxy)\n    output_grid = `Check whether the part row x or column y within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge) has more than two blue points, color all black points red in that row or column`(grid1,x,y,minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\n    return output_grid\ndef color_edge_black_points_red(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    for i in range(minx,maxx + 1):\n        if(input_grid[i][miny] == black):\n            input_grid[i][miny] = red \n        if(input_grid[i][maxy] == black):\n            input_grid[i][maxy] = red \n    \n    for j in range(miny,maxy + 1):\n        if(input_grid[minx][j] == black):\n            input_grid[minx][j] = red\n        if(input_grid[maxx][j] == black):\n            input_grid[maxx][j] = red\n    \n    return input_grid\n    \ndef color_black_points_red_in_row_or_column_with_more_than_two_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray, x: int, y: int, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int):\n    row = input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, y]\n    col = input_grid[x, miny + 1:maxy]\n    if np.count_nonzero(row == blue) >= 2:\n        input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, y][input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, y] == black] = red\n    elif np.count_nonzero(col == blue) >= 2:\n        input_grid[x, miny + 1:maxy][input_grid[x, miny + 1:maxy] == black] = red\n    return input_grid", "gpt_code": "def find_blue_points(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and returns the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of four integers (minx, miny, maxx, maxy) representing the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of all the blue points in the grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid == blue)\n    minx, miny = np.min(blue_points, axis=1)\n    maxx, maxy = np.max(blue_points, axis=1)\n    return (minx, miny, maxx, maxy)\ndef find_blue_points_within_area(input_grid: np.ndarray, minx: int, miny: int, maxx: int, maxy: int) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates of an area and returns the coordinates of the blue point within that area.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (n, m) containing integers from 0 to 9 representing different colors.\n    minx: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate of the area.\n    miny: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate of the area.\n    maxx: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate of the area.\n    maxy: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate of the area.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of two integers (x, y) representing the coordinates of the blue point within the area.\n    \"\"\"\n    blue_points = np.where(input_grid[minx + 1:maxx, miny + 1:maxy] == blue)\n    if blue_points[0].size == 0:\n        return (-1, -1)\n    x, y = (blue_points[0][0] + minx + 1, blue_points[1][0] + miny + 1)\n    return (x, y)", "holes": {"find_blue_points": "find all blue points in the grid, return its min x,min y, max x, max y coordinate", "find_blue_points_within_area": "find blue points within the area [minx:maxx,miny:maxy] (not including the edge), return its coordinate"}}
